@node gAppMode "Application Mode"

	An alternative method of transmitting cursor movement codes.
@endnode


@node gARexx "ARexx"

	A scripting language with the capability to communicate between 
	programs.
@endnode


@node gANSI "ANSI"

	American National Standards Institute.  In reference to 
	telecommunications, this most likely refers to ANSI's standard 
	command set for moving the cursor, and changing text colors over 
	serial lines.
@endnode


@node gASCII "ASCII"

	American Standard Code for Information Interchange.  A widely 
	accepted method of encoding letters, numbers, and symbols into a 
	digital form that computers can process.
@endnode


@node gASCIISend "ASCII Send"

	(verb) To send a text file to another compuuter, one character at a 
			time.
@endnode


@node gAutoBaud "AutoBaud"

	The process of matching the computer-to-modem communications speed 
	to the modem-to-modem communications speed when a connection is 
	established.
@endnode


@node gBackslashCodes "Backslash Codes"

	These codes may be embedded in strings.  They are interpreted by 
	Termite to take a certain action.  See @{"Backslash Codes" link BackslashCodes}
	for a list.
@endnode

@node gBaud "Baud"

	A measure of communications speed.  Technically not the same as 
	BPS, but many people use the terms interchangeably.
@endnode


@node gBBS "BBS"

	Bulletin Board System.  Computers set up to provide user-to-user 
	interaction or files, as a hobby or business.
@endnode


@node gBit "Bit"

	The smallest possible unit of digital data.  Has the value of either 
	one or zero.
@endnode


@node gBPS "BPS"

	Bits per second.  A measure of serial communications speed.
@endnode


@node gButtonBar "Button Bar"

	A window containing user-definable "shortcut" buttons.
@endnode


@node gByte "Byte"

	A unit of computer storage.  On your Amiga, 8 bits as a group.  
	Some other computers use 7 bits per byte.  
@endnode


@node gCapture "Capture"

	(verb) To store incoming data into a file, for later reference.
	(noun) The file created by capturing.
@endnode


@node gCR "Carriage Return"

	(Carriage Return)
	
	The ASCII code that tells a terminal to return the cursor to the 
	beginning of the line.
@endnode


@node gCarrier "Carrier"

	The signal that a modem listens to that indicates there is another 
	modem on the other end of the line.
@endnode


@node gChatWindow "Chat Window"

	A mechanism to make user-to-user chats easier.  Allows you to enter 
	and edit an entire line of text before it is sent to the modem.
@endnode


@node gClip "Clip"

	(noun) Text copied to the clipboard.  See "Copying and pasting".
@endnode


@node gCPS "CPS"

	Characters per second.  A measurement of serial/modem throughput.
@endnode


@node gCursor "Cursor"

	An indicator of where the next character you type will appear.  On 
	the Amiga, this is usually a small colored block.
@endnode


@node gDataBits "Data Bits"

	The number of bits per byte.
@endnode


@node gDownload "Download"

	(verb) To receive a file from another computer.
@endnode


@node gDTR "DTR"

	Data Terminal Ready.  A hardware signal indicating that the 
	computer is ready to communicate with the serial port.  
@endnode


@node gDTRTransition "DTR Transition"

	The DTR signal has changed from on to off.  Many modems interpret 
	this to mean that the computer has terminated communications, and 
	that they should hang up.
@endnode


@node gDuplex "Duplex"

	In Termite's case, duplex is synonymous with local echo.  Half 
	duplex turns local echo on.  Full duplex turns it off.
@endnode


@node gFont "Font"

	A typeface, or style of lettering.
@endnode


@node gHandshaking "Handshaking"

	Control signals that modems use to start and stop the other modem 
	sending data.  Also known as flow control.
@endnode


@node gHayes "Hayes command set"

	A standard set of modem control commands, designed by Hayes.

	See also: @{" Hayes command summary " link HayesCommands }	
@endnode


@node gHotKey "Hot key"

	The key or key sequence that activates a macro.
@endnode


@node gInitString "Init String"

	The command sequence sent to the modem to configure it to your 
	preference.
@endnode


@node gKermit "Kermit"

	A transfer protocol.
@endnode


@node gLF "Line Feed" 

		(Line Feed)

		The ASCII code which tells a terminal to advance to the next line 
		on the display.
@endnode	


@node gLocalEcho "Local Echo"

	If turned on, each character is displayed on the terminal window 
	before being sent to the serial port.
@endnode


@node gLocale "Locale"

	Information pertinent to your country's standards of telling time 
	and measuring currency.
@endnode


@node gMacro "Macro"

	A "shortcut" that does a complex action with a single keypress.
@endnode


@node gMacroEditor "Macro Editor"

	The facility with which you create macros.
@endnode


@node gMacroList "Macro List"

	A list of your currently defined macros, allowing you to click on a 
	macro to activate it, instead of pressing the hot key.
@endnode


@node gModem "Modem"		

	MOdulator/DEModulator.  A computer peripheral which converts serial 
	data into audible tones, which can be transmitted over standard 
	telephone lines, and vice-versa.
@endnode


@node gPath "Path"

	The directory location of a file or group of files on your computer.
@endnode


@node gParity "Parity"

	A primitive method of error checking in communications.
@endnode

		
@node gPen "Pen"

	A way of specifying which color should be used for which drawing 
	operation.
@endnode


@node gPhonebook "Phonebook"

	A database of the systems that you call frequently, their 
	telephone numbers, and their configuration information.
@endnode


@node gProtocol "Protocol"

	Usually refers to transfer protocol.
@endnode


@node gPublicScreen "Public Screen"

	A screen owned by one program that allows other programs to open 
	windows on it.
@endnode


@node gResultCode "Result Code"

	After sending a command string to the modem, it will respond with a 
	result code, such as "OK", "ERROR", or "NO CARRIER".
@endnode


@node gReviewBuffer "Review Buffer"		

	A storage area for incoming serial data.  Enables you to look back 
	over information that is no longer visible on the terminal window.
@endnode


@node gScreenMode "Screen Mode"

	Collectively refers to the resolution, size, and number of colors 
	of the Amiga's display screen.
@endnode


@node gScript "Script"

	A short program written to automate commonly repeated tasks.
@endnode


@node gSerialData "Serial Data"

	Data transmitted to/from the serial port.  The data is sent 1 bit 
	at a time (serially), instead of many bits at a time (parallel).
@endnode


@node gSerialDevice "Serial Device"

	The software driver that knows how to send information to the 
	serial port.
@endnode


@node gSerialPort "Serial Port"

	The socket on the rear of your Amiga that the modem connects to.
@endnode


@node gSerialUnit "Serial Unit"

	The serial device has different "units", which might refer to 
	different serial ports.
@endnode


@node gStatusWindow "Status Window"

	A window on the Termite screen containing information about the 
	time, date, and current connection.
@endnode


@node gStopBits "Stop Bits"

	Additional bits sent at the end of data bits to signal the end 
	of a piece of data.
@endnode


@node gString "String"

	A sequence of letters, numbers, and/or symbols.
@endnode


@node gSysAdmin "SysAdmin"

	System administrator
@endnode


@node gSysOp "SysOp"

	System operator
@endnode


@node gTerminal "Terminal"

	An input/output device for a computer, usually consisting of a 
	display screen and a keyboard.  Can be physically connected to the 
	computer, or via a modem.
@endnode


@node gTransfer "Transfer"

	(verb) To send/receive a file to/from another computer.
	(noun) The process of transferring.
@endnode


@node gTransferProtocol "Transfer Protocol"

	The algorithm that is used to transfer a file.  Both computers must 
	use the same transfer protocol to do a succesful transfer.
@endnode


@node gUpload "Upload"

	(verb) To send a file from your computer to another.
@endnode


@node gUploadDock "Upload Dock"

	An icon that Termite will add to your Workbench while running that 
	allows you to add files to the upload list by dropping their icons 
	onto it.
@endnode


@node gUploadList "Upload List"

	A list of files you intend to upload.
@endnode


@node gVT "VT"

	A series of terminals designed by Digital Equipment Corporation.
@endnode


@node gXEM "XEM"

	External emulation.  An external terminal emulation library designed 
	to emulate a specific type of terminal.  
@endnode


@node gXMODEM "XMODEM"

	A transfer protocol.
@endnode


@node gXPR "XPR"

	External transfer protocol.  A transfer protocol contained in an 
	external library, separate from the main Termite program.
@endnode	


@node gYMODEM "YMODEM"

	A transfer protocol.
@endnode


@node gZMODEM "ZMODEM"

	Probably the most commonly used transfer protocol.
@endnode	


